<p><strong>Western Side-blotched Lizard (<em>Uta stansburiana</em>)</strong></p>
<p><strong>Family: </strong>Phrynosomatidae<br />
<strong>Genus Species: </strong><em>Uta stansburiana</em><br />
<strong>Common Name: </strong>Western Side-blotched Lizard <br /><p>
<p><strong>Identification</strong></p>
<p> The Southern Alligator Lizard has a body length of 1.5 - 2.5 inches. It has a white or gray mostly unmarked belly with dark blue-black marks behind the front limbs, sometimes these marks are faint or absent. Its back is covered in small smooth scales with larger scales on the head and limbs. Its body color is brown, gray, yellowish, or black, with dark blotches or stripes. Males sometimes are speckled with blue. 〔<a href="http://www.californiaherps.com/lizards/pages/u.s.elegans.html">California Herps</a>〕.</p>
<p><strong> </strong></p>
<p><strong>Habitat Associations and Natural History</strong></p>
<p>This lizard can be found inopen rocky areas with scattered vegetation, including hardpan, sandy, rocky, and loamy areas. These lizards are active during the day and during warm weather and is one of the most commonly seen lizard in desert areas. Males are often seen doing push-ups which is a behavior used to mark their territory.It eats small invertebrates such as beetles, grasshoppers, ants, spiders, scorpions and ticks. Females lay 1 - 7 clutches of 1 -8 eggs between March and August.</p>
